ng></em> <strong>4 in</strong>:</p>
<p><em><strong>A =3D</strong></em> <strong>4 in =C3=97 (6 in + 5 in)/2</str=
ong><br>
<em><strong>A =3D</strong></em> <strong>4 in =C3=97 (11 in)/2</strong><br>
<em><strong>A =3D</strong></em> <strong>4 in =C3=97 5.5 in</strong><br>
<em><strong>A =3D</strong></em> <strong>22 in<sup>2</sup></strong></p>
<p>If the formula seems confusing to you, you can follow these steps to obt=
ain the result:</p>
<ol>
<li>Sum the bases of the trapezoid. In this case: <em><strong>a + b</strong=
></em> <strong>=3D 6 in + 5 in =3D 11 in</strong></li>
<li>Divide the previous result by two. In this case: <strong>(11 in)/2 =3D =
5.5 in</strong></li>
<li>Multiply the previous result by the height. In this case: <strong>4 in =
=C3=97 5.5 in =3D 22 in</strong></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>But what if you don't know <em><strong>h</strong></em>?</strong>=
 Let's see how to find the trapezoid height.</p>
</div></div><div class=3D"contentPart css-12zi0x1"><h2 id=3D"how-to-find-th=
e-height-of-a-trapezoid">How to find the height of a trapezoid</h2>
<div class=3D"textBlock"><p>The equation to find the height relies on trigo=
nometric functions. The formula is:</p>
<p><em><strong>h =3D c =C3=97 sin(=CE=B1) =3D d =C3=97 sin(=CE=B4)</strong>=
</em></p>
<p>As you can see, to calculate the height, you need to know:</p>
<ul>
<li>The side <em><strong>c</strong></em> and the angle <em><strong>=CE=B1</=
strong></em>; or</li>
<li>The side <em><strong>d</strong></em> and the angle <em><strong>=CE=B4</=
strong></em>.</li>
</ul>
